               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. MONTAGU WILLIAMS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CAVENDISH BENTINCKE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Prosecuted.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-487" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-487" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-487" type="surname" value="FULLAGAR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-487" type="given" value="WALTER HORNE"></interp>WALTER HORNE FULLAGAR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a solicitor at 7, Renfrew Road, Lower Kennington Lane—prior to the 10th March I was ill and unable to attend to my business—the prisoner called at my house on 10th March, but I did not see him—he called again on the 12th Or 13th, and spoke to me about the result of a matter he had in hand in the police-court, and said, "Now, with regard to my attending to the business for you, shall I account to you daily or in what way?" and he said: "All cases that can afford agency I should expect agency in; but the smaller cases I should be happy to do for nothing"—I said, "Certainly not, Mr. May, I shall do nothing of the kind"—I said first of all, "I cannot be troubled with any accounts; I cannot expect you to do my business except upon condition that you receive one-half of all the fees you take at the police-court, be good enough to keep an exact account of what you receive and pay away and then when I am well enough we can see what money there is coming to me'—the next day he sent up 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. to me—the conversation took place in my bedroom—on 3rd April I saw him again in my parlour with a client who had instructed me to prosecute a man named Lytton, and I advised him, in May's presence, and a day or so afterwards I asked May what counsel he intended having, as I should like Mr. Besley to lead—he said "I should like to give young Mr. Metcalfe a brief." I said "Certainly." I do not know Mr. Metcalfe, but I should like Mr. Besley to lead; do not mark Mr. Besley's brief, less than seven guineas and two guineas, and do not mark Mr. Metcalfe's brief, if you engage him, less than four and one," and I drew a cheque for Â£20 and handed it to May—I went out of town for a week, and saw May on 22nd April, on my return—I asked him</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300201"></xptr>
               <p>how Lytton's matter was going on, and said, "Is there anything more you want to say to me?"—he said "Oh, yes, I shall want some more money in that case of Lytton's." I said "Have you spent all that £20?"—he said "Oh, yes, I had to have several conferences with Besley and Metcalfe, and had to pay them their consultations and the fees on their briefs, and the prosecutors are going on with the indictment in Davis's case; I therefore had to brief Besley and Metcalfe in that as well—I said, "Very well, Mr. May, if you have spent the money properly I bad better give you some more," and, belie ring his statement, I drew and handed him a cheque for £15—on the 22nd April a lady called at my office and from information received I made inquiries as to whether he had been in consultation with Messrs. Besley and Metcalfe, and afterwards saw May at the Middlesex Sessions—I said, "Where are the briefs and papers?"—he said, "I have got them, and I mean to keep them!"—I said, "You had better mind what you are doing. I shall give you until 10 o'clock to-morrow morning, and if you do not hand them over to me by that time you must take the consequences," and next morning I received this (<hi rend="italic">Letter "C"</hi>), which is in his handwriting. ("77, Chancery Lane, 23rd April, 1879, <hi rend="italic">Reg. v. Lytton, and several prosecutions.</hi> I will be at your place with papers, &amp;c., and list of items of expenditure to<lb></lb>morrow at 10.30. You will no doubt, with your usual sense of propriety and professional honour, feel it just to make me some substantial remunera<lb></lb>tion, in lieu of agency, for the care and labour bestowed on this case in now bringing it to an issue: I shall be happy to afford you every informa<lb></lb>tion respecting any other matter I may have been concerned in. I shall, however, have to adopt the ordinary means of protecting myself against the results of your threats. Notwithstanding the effect of the statements of the plausible widow, whose claim (especially under the circumstances) would have been settled long ago, <hi rend="italic">if just</hi>, and whom you sent up by my discharged clerk simply to annoy me, I have the satisfaction of believing you will, on inquiry, credit me with having treated you and regarded your interests in a gentlemanly and conscientious way. As you referred to the subject, I may inform you, if it interests you, that, believing it to be the duty of a man (if it be possible) to have his wife under his own roof, arrangements are now being made to this end. How often does it happen in life that when one is in the act of retrieving the past, that past comes or ward in some shape or other, and prevents his accomplishing the ends desired. This portion of my letter is written aurente catarne, and I trust to your honour to let it remain private. Yours'truly, Alfred H. May.") The next day, the 24th, before I had received that letter, he came to my office and handed me Lytton's papers—I said "Now, where is the money?"—he said, "Oh, what money?"—I said "That 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. you got. from me"—he said "Oh! that's a matter of account"—I had not then seen the briefs—I said "A matter of account! What do you mean? I handed you first 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and then 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for that special purpose, I want to know what you have done with it"—he said "Oh! that is a matter of account"—I said "I do not understand what you mean by a matter of account; I want to know what you have done with that money which you obtained from me for that sole purpose"—I said "There is the money you have taken since you have been here, and I have not received that"—he said "That is a matter of arrangement"—I said "That is enough. Go</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300202"></xptr>
               <p>away"—he said "Will you let me make out a statement?"—I said "You can do what you like, so long as you go out of my office," and he made out a statement and brought it to me—I said "How dare you make out this, and call this a statement? I know nothing about this. Have you got the money? Are you going to hand me over the money?"—he said "No, I have not got it"—I subsequently gave him notice and took proceedings against him before Mr. Chance.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by the Prisoner.</hi> I have seen you at the Thames Police Court once—I cannot say I have known you as a Criminal and County Court advocate, but I have heard you were—I have not heard that you have practised your profession with success in the advocacy department, but quite the contrary—that did not induce me to enter into an arrange<lb></lb>ment with you to conduct my criminal cases—I have gained the informa<lb></lb>tion since I had you—probably I said before the Magistrate, "On the 10th March, in consequence of my illness, I was obliged to get some one to superintend my business, and the prisoner called at my house and offered to give me some assistance. I spoke to him and told him I should be very happy to have his assistance, and said, 'I am afraid it will interfere too much with your business.' He said, 'No; my partner Lewis can attend to that'"—I am not pasitive whether it was the 10th or 12th—you first called on the 10th, but I believe I did not see you till the 12th; but I have the papers here, and can show you—I did not say it was on the 10th—you called on the 10th, and transacted the first business for me on the 10th, but I think it was the 12th I first saw you—on the 12th I sent to Sergeant 'n wood to say that Mr. May would attend to all my cases—you attended to some cases on the Monday before I saw you.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. Serjeant In wood, is the summoning officer of the Lambeth Police Court—when parties called at the Court to see me when 1 was ill he would be obliged to tell them—the police do not interfere.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the Prisoner.</hi> I swore before the Magistrates: "A few days after<lb></lb>wards he came up himself into my bedroom—that was the first time I met you, and it was then this conversation took places—there was no one present—I was in bed—Mr. Hambro, Cashier to Cross, Sons, and Riley, Solicitors, was in my room when the instructions came in the Queen v. Lytton, and Mr. Purver was there—he was the nominal prosecutor in the case—this (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) is my handwriting. (Copy. "To Mr. Purver. 5th April, 1879. Dear Sir. Reg. v. Lytton. Felony. I hereby acknow<lb></lb>ledge that although you have instructed me to prosecute the above-named person for felony at the ensuing Middlesex Sessions, I do not hold you personally liable for the costs of that prosecution. Walter H. Fullagar.")</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. I should have got my costs from my clients direct, Messrs. Cross, Sons, and Riley—Mr. Purver was obliged to be the prose<lb></lb>cutor, because he was the administrator of his late sister—Mr. Purver was a poor man, and could not stand the expenses, and would not have allowed his name to be given as prosecutor if I had not told him he would not be liable for the costs.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the Prisoner.</hi> Hambro did not tell me in your presence that a gentleman of property, a client of Cross, Sons, and Riley had, instructed them to find out some person to prosecute Lytton—it is not a fact that when I placed Hambro in your bands to conduct this prosecution, I informed you that Hambro's employers, Cross, Sons, and Riley, had a country client</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300203"></xptr>
               <p>who for certain reasons guaranteed the expenses of the prosecution—Mr. Hambro asked me what I thought the cost of the prosecution would be, and whether 25<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. would cover it, and my answer was, Yes, I thought it would; and you answered "Yes, a great deal can be done for 25<hi rend="italic">l</hi>."—I can<lb></lb>not say that the expenses of the prosecution are being paid by a client of Cross, Sons, and Riley—I cannot say who in fact did pay—I do not know who the real prosecutor is—I have my instructions from Cross, Sons, and Riley, and have seen no one else except Mr. Purver—I did not tell you the reasons why the real prosecutor should be undiscovered—I did not know myself—I did not inquire—Lytton was already in custody upon charges of misdemeanour, and this case, which was to be heard on the following Monday at the Middlesex Sessions, was a further charge—I cannot say whether you had an immense deal of work to do in procuring evidence for the further indict<lb></lb>ment—I have every reason to know you did not do it—I received one or two letters from you—I may have remarked to my son," May is indeed energetic about these things: he was up last Sunday night till one o'clock"—I thought you were doing your duty—I do not admit that you pre<lb></lb>pared the evidence and compiled two briefs and statements; you did not do it—you handed something to Mr. Besley—I have the brief here—the outside sheet is impounded, and attached to the depositions—I admit you handed something you called a brief, and which was marked as a brief, but it is not what I call a brief, it was a skeleton—I am not continuing that prosecution against Lytton—I am continuing a prosecution against him in the next Court for forgery—I am indemnifying the expenses of the prose<lb></lb>cution—Purser is not paying, he is only a poor man—Messrs, Cross instruct me, and I look to them for payment—I do not know who they look to—I do not recollect your saying that you were doubtful whether "it was a proper course to pursue, and not a course you would yourself pursue—no mention was made of the remuneration you were to receive—it was one of the matters that came into the office, and had you attended to that properly you would have received an equal share of the costs with myself, as in any other business—I might have said, "There is no necessity to pay Mr. Besley, my name at the bottom of any brief is good enough"—that might have been when I gave you the 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., but I believe it was a week afterwards, when I came from Ayling Island—at the time I advanced the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. I knew that Lytton's case bad been to the Sessions, and you told me you had had these consultations with Mr. Besley and Mr. Metcalfe, and that it bad been adjourned—I was not at the Sessions—I know now that at the time the 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. was advanced the case had been to the Sessions, and the briefs handed to counsel, and fees paid, and everything done so far—I cannot say that you had done all that was necessary to bring it to the Sessions and have it adjourned—it was adjourned—I did not know, as a matter of fact, that, having gone so far with the case, you had expended money in divers other expenses for witnesses, conduct money, subpoenas, cabs, etc., besides counsels' fees; I naturally supposed it—you told me you had, and I believed you—you told me that, in addition, you were instructed by my clients to prepare a further indictment against Lytton—I do not know it now as a fact—I know there was an indictment—I know only that I have had to pay all the fees to counsel—you never paid a penny fee—you drew an indictment, and as a true bill</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300204"></xptr>
               <p>was found I suppose you went before the Grand Jury, and no doubt in this farther case you went that far—I cannot say that I had advanced the 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. before that was done—I advanced it on 22nd April, but do not know when the bill, went before the Grand Jury, I never inquired—I remarked that if you had spent the money "I had better give you another cheque for 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.," and you said, "Well, I should think 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. would be enough;" I said, "No, you had better have one for 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. if you have paid all that money away"—I understood from you that you had paid other expenses; you must have spent money in other costs besides counsels' fees; you cannot go about in a cab or an omnibus without spending other money—you did not tell me you had expended the whole of the money in counsels' fees and consultations—when I advanced the 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.I dare say you supposed I was going into the country the next day—I told you so and I meant to go, and it is quite possible you would have carried on Lytton's case in my absence, and at the late you were going you might have required 500<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—the costs in the case will come to quite 500<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I did no doubt swear before the Magistrates "The case of Lytton was of a very hurried character, and being hurried may increase the expenses"—the lady, Mrs. Hodges, came on the 23rd, the day after you had the 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—you were at the Middlesex Sessions, but I do not know what you were engaged in—when you came back I heard what Mrs. Hodges said to you, and I asked you whether you could answer it—she had nothing to do with Lytton's case—I was not drink<lb></lb>ing with her—I believe she had some spirits and a biscuit—I did not know her till my housekeeper introduced her to me, amd I told the housekeeper to let her have what she wanted, some biscuits and a sandwich—this is my handwriting; I sent it on 25th April; I sent it to you the day after the interview. (<hi rend="italic">Read:</hi> "6, Renfrew Road, Lower Kennington Lane, London, S.E. 25th April, 1879. Sir, From what I am obliged to hear almost hourly I am quite convinced that you intended to feloniously misappro<lb></lb>priate the 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. you obtained from me on the 22nd instant, under the pretence and assertion that you had expended the 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. I advanced you a few days before in counsels' fees and other payments out of pocket in the case against Lytton, and for which the money was solely and expressly advanced. This statement I now find to be utterly false, but I do not like to apply for a warrant against you without first informing you of my intention to do so next Monday before Mr. Chance. Yours obediently, Walter H. Fullagar. Mr. May, Solicitor, 77, Chancery Lane.")—a warrant was issued on Monday, May 1st.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. A summons could not have been obtained; it might possibly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the Prisoner.</hi> I know you said your office was 77, Chancery Lane, and it is in the Law List—my only reason for speak ing of you as absconding in the information was that you were not at your office, and I tried to find you—I believe you were apprehended in London—in accordance with your letter of the 23rd you came to me next morning, about 10 or a little later, and Mr. Hambro was with me—the case was to come on again—I do not know if it was the following day—you brought the papers and put them down on my desk, but I cannot say what observation you made—I was waiting for the papers—you went into the back office and came back again in about 15 minutes and handed me this account (<hi rend="italic">Headed "Items of Expenditure re Lyitom; and containg details of'counsels'fees, cab fares, &amp;c., total</hi> 19<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 0<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300205"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">and on the same sheet a supplemental account of</hi> 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.)—you handed me that account and all the papers—you may have done that work.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. I do not dispute or deny that he has paid those moneys—I admit that he has, but the 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. was solely for Lytton's case—the supple mental bill he makes out of 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. has nothing to do with Mr. Besley's case.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the Prisoner.</hi> When you gave me the account you said something about having marked the items alphabetically, referring to the lists of items on the backs of the papers, and that I should find all the items by referring to the letters—I cannot say whether you wrote the items in pencil at the time—you have had no opportunity of writing them since I have had it, and they were upon it when I received it—when I advanced the first 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. you had money of mine amounting to 40<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and the 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. made about 60<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—the other sums were a matter of account—they were received by you, to be accounted for to me as a matter of account—the one set of sums were received from clients on account, but this was money received from me—the money was only half mine—you did not ask me if I was perfectly satisfied, and I did not say, "I suppose I must be"—I think I said, "How dare you hand me such an account as this?"—you said before the Magis<lb></lb>trate, "If you cannot treat me like a gentleman I cannot manage any further business for you"—you made some remark about calling on Monday or Tuesday, and I told you never to come near my house again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-488" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-488" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-488" type="surname" value="LOCKYER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-488" type="given" value="HENRY WILLIAM"></interp>HENRY WILLIAM LOCKYER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Besley, Mr. Besley was retained for the prosecution in the Queen v. Lytton by May, and I received 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. Od. fees—that is all I have received from May, I had no other consultations from him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I have known you some time, and this is not the first brief you have handed me—you paid me the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. Od. on the adjourn<lb></lb>ment at the Court, and I presume you knew there would bean adjournment and further fees to pay—I hardly think you have paid similar fees before—you have paid larger fees—it was 3 guineas and a consultation—I saw you afterwards with Mr. Hambro outside Mr. Besley's chambers, but do not know whether you saw him—I believe you did, and had a conversation—I have the fees, but the other clerk books the attendances—the fees booked were inclusive of the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. Od,—the other consultations were booked to Mr. Fullagar—I believe you had only the consultation on the brief; the others were by Mr. Fullagar and Mr. Hambro—the special consultation you had was subsequent to the adjournment.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WILLIAMS</hi>. He never paid me more than the one consultation marked on the brief.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. I entered it as "May's matter "as though he were the Solicitor, and afterwards in Mr. Fullagar's name—they were entered in the day-book when I returned to the office as "Mr. W. May paid Mr. Besley's fee "so and so, and then afterwards "Mr. Fullagar."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-489" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-489" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-489" type="surname" value="NORTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-489" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD NORTH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Mr. Metcalfe's clerk—on the 9th April at the Middlesex Sessions, May handed me a brief—I asked him what he was going to mark—he said three guineas—I said, "You mean three and one," and he said, "Mr. Fullagar said I was not to give you more than three"—I said, "Then, being two counsel in the case, we must have consulta<lb></lb>tion," and he said "Put down two and one"—he paid me, and I initialled the brief and dated it—I had no other fee at all.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300206"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> Two guineas and a "con "would be a proper fee to mark when the senior has three and a "con"—you told me you had to draw an indictment and present it to the brand Jury yourself after Mr. Metcalfe had drawn the indictment—on your paying me for the brief I said "There's the fee for drawing the indictment"—you said, "Oh, I've had to do it over again, and I cannot give you the fee"—you have given me several briefs before—you saw Mr. Metcalfe personally.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-490" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-490" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-490" type="surname" value="CHAMBERLAIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-490" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM CHAMBERLAIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Police Inspector L</hi>). On 5th May I received a warrant for May's apprehension, and went to his office, but could not find him—I searched for him till Saturday night, 24th May, when I saw him in Chippendale Road—I said, "I have a warrant for your apprehension for obtaining money from Mr. Fullagar;" he said, "Oh dear, yes, Mr. Chamberlain. It is a very unfortunate affair. I gave a friend of mine, Mr. Lewis, a cheque twice to settle the matter, and I am afraid he has not done so; if you had not taken me, I was thinking of giving myself up. I have come over from the country on purpose to do so"—on taking him in custody he gave me two pieces of paper, saying, "These papers refer to Lytton's case, and belong to Mr. Fullagar."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-491" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-491" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-491" type="surname" value="KERSTEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-491" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KERSTEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep the White Swan, 225, High Street, Shad<lb></lb>well—on July 20th I had a case on, and this claim was made for 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and I considered I owed only 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I saw May respecting it, and showed him this letter I had received the same day from the plaintiff's Solicitors. (<hi rend="italic">Read:</hi> "32, Mark Lane, London, E.C., 24th July, 1878. Sir,—We are instructed by Messrs. Murrow and Holt, of 18, City Road, Finsbury, to apply to you for payment of 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., amount of account rendered. Unless we receive this sum, with 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for our charges, by 10 o'clock on Friday morning next, we shall at once proceed to recover same. Yours obediently, Keene &amp; Marsland. F. Harris." May said, "It was foolish of you to have offered him the 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., because, as he did into fulfil the contract, you had nothing to pay; but now you have offered him the 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. you will have to pay it"—and so I gave him the 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to pay it into Court—he called on me about three weeks afterwards, and said, "We can't settle the affair in any other way; we shall have to go to the Lord Mayor's Court;" and he wanted 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and I gave it him, as he said he had engaged Mr. Besley to plead for me—he gave me no receipt, he only marked it on one of the papers in his pocket. (<hi rend="italic">Paper marked "C":</hi> "7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. paid on account.") I saw him subsequently in September at my place, and I asked him how the affair was going on, and he said it was put back for the Long Vacation—I did not see him again—he did not appear for me, and the end of it was, I found the brokers in the house on the 31st October for 37<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 14<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and I had to pay them out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> The 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. was paid into Court—it has not come to my knowledge that it was paid into Court at the proper time, but that on account of the plea not having been delivered by your clerk in proper time the other side signed judgment—the 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. was advanced to pay Mr. Besley—I recollect your telling him you were en leave ring to settle the matter with Keene and Marsland, and if you had settled it for 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. I should have been satisfied—you did not tell me you had offered Keene and Marsland 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to settle, and I know nothing of it—I gave you full dis<lb></lb>creation as Solicitor to act for me—I saw Mr. Beck, Solicitor, and told him where to find you, and he said he would write you a letter, but I do not know whether he has been in correspondence with you.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300207"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. I was not asked by any one to prosecute—I wrote to Mr. Fullagar when I saw it in the paper.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-492" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-492" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-492" type="surname" value="SPIEGELBATER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-492" type="given" value="ALBERT"></interp>ALBERT SPIEGELBATER</persName>
                  </hi>.—I am a watchmaker at 62, The Mount, White<lb></lb>Chapel Road, Mr. Kersten is a friend of mine—I remember being in his house about the middle of August, when May, in my presence, asked him for 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and said he had engaged Mr. Besley, and had to pay him the money—no receipt was given.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I was there till you went away, sitting opposite you in the bar parlour—I came through the bar—I did not see you write the receipt produced, and nothing more was said than what I have stated—you did not remain long after you had the money—I was first asked the week before last to come forward as a witness—I did not think anything more of it, but I recollected well enough after I was told—I was surprised to see in the papers that criminal proceedings were being taken against you, but I did not think anything of it then.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-493" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-493" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-493" type="surname" value="LOCKYER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-493" type="given" value="HENRY WILLIAM"></interp>HENRY WILLIAM LOCKYER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Re-examined</hi>). I did not receive 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or any money in respect of an action against Kersten in the Lord Mayor's Court, and Mr. Besley was not instructed in the matter at all.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> You had cases with me about that time—I should have recollected if you had said, 'I may want you for other cases in the Mayor's Court," but I should not recollect if you said, "I shall want you for another case shortly."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witnesses for the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-494" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-494" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-494" type="surname" value="HAMBRO"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-494" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY HAMBRO</persName>
                  </hi>. I am cashier to Messrs. Cross, Sons, and Riley, Waterloo Place—on 3rd April I-called on Mr. Fullagar and gave him instructions to proceed with a fresh indictment in Lytton's case—he said he had not been very well and had got a gentleman attending to his busi<lb></lb>ness who would conduct the case in his absence, and he called you in and introduced you—Mr. Purver was present, and it was arranged that I should put myself in your hands, and you were to conduct the case—it was an Ordinary case; I cannot say what interest our client took in it—it was necessary, the time being short, for us to go about every night for witnesses, and we went about a good deal to gather materials for the case—we were going about and spending money—you made pencil notes which 1 believed to be items of expenditure in the case, but I did not examine them, and during the whole time we were together you paid all the expenses—I had not to pay; it was not a matter I could expend money in—you attended diligently to the case, and to the best of my recollection when you left the case you had all the witnesses before the Grand Jury in the second indictment in Davis's case, when Mr. Fullagar came up in a rage at the Court the day the case was coming on—I cannot remember how many adjournments had taken place—I was present on the 23rd when you handed Mr. Fullagar the papers—Mr. Fullagar appeared to say as little as he could—he was certainly out of temper at the Sessions House but not then—I heard you offer to make out an account, which you did in the adjoining room—I have tried but cannot remember complete sentences of what was said—I recollect him saying something to this effect: "Even those figures would show that you have not accounted for about 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.," and I think you said "Very well;" and I remember you saying there would be some remuneration due to you for what you had done for him.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187906300208"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I decline to say who our client was in prosecuting Lytton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18790630-name-495" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-495" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-495" type="surname" value="KEENE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18790630-name-495" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS KEENE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a member of the firm of Keene, Sons, and Mars<lb></lb>land, Solicitors—I was instructed in the case of Murrow. v. Kersten—you attended at my office, and a correspondence took place between us—you offered 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. without costs in settlement of the case, which declined—you elected to fight the case and paid the money into Court—judgment was signed on the 16th October, and the plea was not sent to my office till the 17th, which was too late—had the plea been dlivered on the proper day, or a day after, I should not have signed judgment.</p>
